          <h3><span class="highlight">Captain</span> Saefinn Liljasson</h3>
        <h4>The Scholar Captain</h4>
        <img src="http://i.imgur.com/U5MRo5N.png"></img>
        <p class="letter">The brave and daring Saefinn Liljasson, a captain of the people, a true hero among mortals. He has nominations for best Oscar and also the nobel peace prize. He once stopped Taylor Swift mid-speech, not to compliment Beyonce, but to tell the world that he is one of her many ex-boyfriends and that she should call some time.</p>
        <p>All right, that's not what Saefinn is really like, but you almost believed the bit about the Noble Peace prize, didn't you? What do you mean there's no Nobel Prize in Eorzea? I am pretty sure I saw somebody called Taylor Swift at least.</p>
       <p>Saefinn is the formerly drunk captain, now just a captain who tries to figure out how to get drunk, not take it too far and not have anybody notice. He is an idealist, who believes that piracy should not be a free-for-all 'nothing matters' kind of gig, he believes in freedom and believes the laws to be more advisary than actual laws. But he sees an ugliness in the kind of piracy the likes of The Reavers show. To the point where he'll perfectly happily blow them out of the water and leave no survivors. But he doesn't believe in the way of the Maelstrom either, in princple, he believes that yes, people ought to be "good", but the world is too dirty to do things by the book, that it restricts what one can do. And he views that there isn't justice in the Maelstrom way, that innocent people in the wrong place at the wrong time can just end up sharing the same cell as the worst kind of pirate. Particularly with corruption among its ranks. Saefinn never saw light as to why the Admiral thought it a good idea to let Pirates become Privateers. They are still the salty sea bags they were before, but with authority. </p>
        <p>It is behind those ideas that he drives The Pirates of the Wayward Star. He believes in a crew that always watches each other's back, but those who stab a crew mate's back are in for a fate that's not for polite conversation. He believes those who exploit others to be fair game, but those just trying to make it by and are innocent, to be off limits. His family were once the honest types and it got them nowhere but at the bottom of society and they were trampled on. So he has a special spot there.</p>
